          "id": 33243,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Representational</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 33244,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Categorical</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 33245,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Both A and B</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 33246,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Neither A nor B</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 58-year-old patient presents with a history of difficulty reading maps, getting lost in familiar surroundings, and trouble judging distances while driving. Neurological examination reveals intact language and memory functions. MRI scans show atrophy in the parietal lobe of the brain. Which of the following cerebral hemispheres is primarily involved in spatiotemporal and visuospatial relations?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q9868945",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33074,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. A) Representational</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A:&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Correct. The representational (usually the right) hemisphere is primarily involved in <strong>spatiotemporal</strong> and <strong>visuospatial relations</strong>, <strong>non-verbal thinking</strong>, and <strong>image processing</strong>. The patient&#39;s symptoms align with dysfunction in this hemisphere.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Dominant and non-dominant hemispheres:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/27/picture4.jpg\" style=\"height:250px; width:1000px\" /></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Incorrect. The categorical (usually the left) hemisphere is associated with language, logical reasoning, and analytical processing. The patient&#39;s intact language and memory suggest this hemisphere is less affected.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Incorrect. While both hemispheres work together, the representational hemisphere is more directly involved in spatiotemporal and visuospatial processing, as evidenced by the patient&#39;s specific symptoms.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Incorrect. One of the hemispheres, specifically the representational hemisphere, is implicated in the patient&#39;s difficulties with spatial orientation and distances.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The objective is to understand the <strong>functional specialization</strong> of the <strong>cerebral hemispheres</strong>, particularly the role of the representational hemisphere in spatiotemporal and visuospatial processing.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Refer:</span></span></u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Ganong&rsquo;s Review of Medical Physiology, 25<sup>th</sup> Edition, Pg No: 290, 291</span></span></strong></p>",
