      "id": 8320,
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 33247,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Frontal Lobe</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 33248,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Parietal Lobe</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 33249,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Occipital Lobe</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 33250,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Temporal Lobe</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 32-year-old patient presents with sudden difficulty in understanding spoken language and expressing thoughts coherently. Neurological examination reveals no motor deficits, and the patient is intact. Imaging studies indicate damage to the posterior part of the left cerebral hemisphere. The sensory speech area is located in which lobe of the cerebral cortex?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q7954806",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33072,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. D) Temporal Lobe</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D:&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Correct. The sensory speech area, also known as <strong>Wernicke&#39;s area</strong>, is located in the <strong>posterior part</strong> of the <strong>left temporal lobe</strong>. It is crucial for understanding spoken language, and damage to this area can lead to difficulties in language comprehension and fluent speech production.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Wernicke&#39;s area is located in the temporal lobe, shown here in grey:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/27/03.jpg\" style=\"height:447px; width:600px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A:&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Incorrect. The frontal lobe contains the motor speech area (<strong>Broca&#39;s area</strong>) involved in speech production, but it is not primarily responsible for understanding language.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Incorrect. The parietal lobe is involved in processing sensory information and spatial orientation but not in primary language comprehension.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Incorrect. The occipital lobe is the center for visual processing and isnot directly involved in language comprehension.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The objective is to understand the localization and function of key areas in the cerebral cortex, specifically the role of the temporal lobe and Wernicke&#39;s area in language comprehension.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">(<u>Refer:</u> Ganong&rsquo;s Review of Medical physiology, 25<sup>th</sup> edition, pg no: 292)</span></strong></span></span></p>",
